flat, is broadband-- so

01:19:06.720 --> 01:19:09.510
for the extreme
broadband case, we

01:19:09.510 --> 01:19:11.508
can pull that out
of the integral.

01:19:15.870 --> 01:19:19.370
And then, we are left only
with this function, F of t.

01:19:37.950 --> 01:19:46.460
And you can discuss
this function, F of t,

01:19:46.460 --> 01:19:48.190
is a standard result.

01:19:48.190 --> 01:19:50.670
And we have seen
many discussions

01:19:50.670 --> 01:19:51.890
in perturbation theory.

01:19:56.990 --> 01:20:11.590
If I plot this
function, versus delta,

01:20:11.590 --> 01:20:14.035
we have something
which has wiggles.

01:20:14.035 --> 01:20:16.920
Then, there is a maximum,
and it has wiggles.

01:20:20.030 --> 01:20:23.515
The width here is
t to the minus 1.

01:20:28.962 --> 01:20:31.300
And the amplitude is t squared.

01:20:33.900 --> 01:20:37.965
And this is the excited
state amplitude squared.

01:20:51.260 --> 01:20:59.980
So if we integrate
that over delta,

01:20:59.980 --> 01:21:01.970
we get something
which is linear in t.

01:21:01.970 --> 01:21:05.020
Something which goes as
t-square, and has a width 1/t.

01:21:15.650 --> 01:21:16.870
Yes, time is over.

01:21:20.140 --> 01:21:28.460
So the function F of t,
which is under the integrand,

01:21:28.460 --> 01:21:35.660
starts out at short
times, proportion

01:21:35.660 --> 01:21:38.560
to t squared, as we discussed.

01:21:38.560 --> 01:21:41.056
Maybe my drawing
should reflect that.

01:21:45.540 --> 01:21:48.230
But then it becomes linear.

01:21:48.230 --> 01:21:57.920
So for long times, the function
F of t becomes linear in t

01:21:57.920 --> 01:22:00.670
and the delta function
in the detuning delta.

01:22:03.210 --> 01:22:04.870
This is what you
have seen many times

01:22:04.870 --> 01:22:07.390
in the derivation of
Fermi's golden rule.

01:22:07.390 --> 01:22:08.940
I'm running out of time now.

01:22:08.940 --> 01:22:10.880
I'll pick up the
